# Agentic Fullstack Delivery Team

Use this rule when the user asks to turn a Figma design into frontend/backend implementation, run the agentic team, or use `/agentic-team`.

## Agent Profiles

Load and follow the relevant profiles from `.cursor/agents/`:

- `.cursor/agents/project-manager-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/frontend-architect-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/backend-architect-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/developer-subagent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/design-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/accurate-design-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/functional-compatibility-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/integration-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/accessibility-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/performance-optimization-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/security-qa-agent.md`
- `.cursor/agents/documentation-agent.md`

## Required Workflow

1. Repository Discovery
   - Inspect project structure, package scripts, frontend stack, backend stack, styling system, test tools, and existing conventions.
   - Do not edit files during this phase.
2. Figma Understanding
   - Read the provided Figma design/context.
   - Use Figma MCP if available, with a hard limit of one Figma design-context fetch for the current `/agentic-team` invocation.
   - The Project Manager Agent owns the single Figma fetch. Fetch the broadest useful node once, then summarize and share the captured context with all architects, developer subagents, and QA agents.
   - Do not call `get_design_context`, `get_screenshot`, `get_metadata`, or other Figma MCP read tools again during the same invocation unless the user explicitly approves the extra quota use.
   - If the first fetch is incomplete or truncated, continue from the returned context, pasted user context, existing screenshots/assets, and repo docs. Ask the user before spending another Figma MCP call.
   - If Figma MCP is unavailable, work from pasted context and state the limitation.
3. Architecture Planning
   - Frontend Architect creates the frontend plan.
   - Backend Architect creates the backend/API plan when backend changes are needed.
   - Project Manager converts plans into implementation tasks.
4. Implementation
   - Developer Subagents implement one assigned task at a time.
   - Reuse existing code wherever possible.
   - Commit each completed task as a checkpoint if git is available.
5. QA Validation
   - Run Design QA, Accurate Design QA, Functional QA, Integration QA, Accessibility QA, Performance QA, and Security QA as relevant.
6. Fix Loop
   - Project Manager deduplicates and prioritizes issues.
   - Developer Subagents fix assigned issues.
   - Re-run relevant QA after each fix.
7. Final Review
   - Documentation Agent updates docs if needed.
   - Project Manager produces the final report and approval status.
8. Local Server Cleanup
   - Before final approval, stop any local frontend or backend processes started for validation unless the user explicitly asks to keep them running.
   - Cleanup includes repo-local `npm run dev`, `npm run dev:backend`, `next dev`, `next start`, standalone frontend server, and `strapi develop` processes.
   - Prefer tracking and stopping the exact process IDs launched during validation. If PIDs were not tracked, only stop processes whose command lines clearly point to this repository.
   - The Project Manager Agent owns this cleanup gate. QA agents must report any servers they started and whether they were stopped.

## Completion Gate

Do not mark the task complete until:

- The final report states whether the single Figma MCP fetch budget was used, skipped, or explicitly exceeded with user approval.
- All P0 and P1 issues are resolved.
- P2 issues are resolved or explicitly deferred.
- Required QA reports are complete.
- Local frontend and backend verification servers started by the team have been stopped, unless the user explicitly asked to leave them running.
- The Project Manager Agent has reviewed all agent reports.

## Required Final Output

1. Implementation summary
2. Final file changes
3. Components created or reused
4. Backend/API changes
5. Tests/checks run
6. Figma MCP quota usage
7. Design accuracy report
8. Functional QA report
9. Performance report
10. Accessibility report
11. Security report
12. Remaining known issues
13. Manual review checklist
14. Local server cleanup status
15. Final approval status
